113,http://www.armslist.com/posts/2607113,For Sale:  Powder: 16 lbs (or less) sealed jugs of WC-857 (tested right at H870 and MR8700),"Hartford. KS (hour south ot Topeka), Topeka, Kansas",$ 80,"Listed On: Wednesday, April 9, 2014",Ammo,no type,no type,no type,no type,"This ball powder is quite consistent and has proven itself to be a good, diverse go-to for several great loads in several calibers this last year since I got it in May 2013.  I'm ONLY selling what I know I won't shoot in a lifetime here and I've proven the burn rate in many guns so this lot is tested and very stable in all loads I used it in.

Ball powder does typically burn a bit more dirty than stick powders on average, BUT it ALSO burns cooler than IMR4831, IMR4850 and a few other ""popular"" stick powders.  So barrel life is extended using ball powders like this one.  I've shot a lot of Mil-spec ball powder (in standard NATO military loads for 5.56mm) rounds out of my .223 and the same ball powder does leave a bit of ""ash"" in SOME rifles-- which needs cleaning about every 80-100 rounds.  But many stick powders ALSO have this issue (totally depending on the load), so if it's good enough for the military in the desert with AR-15s going all week long-- ball powder is good enough for me ;)
63 grains (a full case in my brass) in my Ruger M-77, 25-06 hits abut 3100 FPS and burns as clean as any other ball power (like Winchester powders at over twice the price).

My 7MM/Mag likes 80 grains (about a full case) at 3100 fps on a 139 gr. bullet.  Again, the burn is slower than some popular powders, but for this caliber a full case (vs. 85-90% case of IMR4831) gets the same velocity as other popular powders; and in my gun-- the same accuracy.  My 800 lb elk shot at 400 yards (in the neck with a Hornady SST 139 gr) this last Dec. went down like they all do when I shoot them with any other powder ;)

My buddy's 300 Weatherby Mag LOVES this stuff and he's slowly replacing his IMR and Hogden powders with this stuff too.  Yet another reloading buddy has used it in his Laupa .338 and is getting good results after some time on his 500 yrd. range!

I bought SIX jugs (8 lbs each) to offset the $30 Hazmat fee and was going to give 1/2 of it to some buddies on a fishing trip, but they couldn't wait and they went and bought theirs already.  So I was just going to keep it, but I realized after a while that I will NEVER use it all.  So I'm keeping three jugs and I have THREE left-- for exactly what I have in them.

SO here's the deal.. I paid $72 a jug plus $50 in shipping (for six) so about $8 a jug for shipping and there is my gas to meet a buyer also.  So $90 a jug (which comes to $11 a lb, BTW) and I have ONE jug left to sell.

I've shot about 2 lbs the last 8 months in five calibers (both reduced loads and full power loads) and have friends in TX and NM who have shot a few rounds this last year-- we all love this stuff.  I have a great ""duplex"" load for my .223 (I really love, 1"" groups at 200 yards through a bold Savage Axis!!), but you have to KNOW (and prove it to me) that you know what you are doing before I give you this load data/method.

Anyway, at $32 a lb at my local store for the ONE lb. ""canister"" of IMR, Hodgden or Alliant powers (which I can't find these days!)--- this stuff shoots as good (and better in more and more cases as I figure it out) for 1/3dr the cost.

It is dead on with H870 in my 7mm/Mag and my buddy's Weatherby 300 Mag. in Sierra's and Speer's books (older 1990 editions).  It also lines up with loads for MR8700 (in my Speer #11 book) too.  If you want a textbook load for these rifles, this powder (I have tested well) fits the books (in the lot I have) like a glove for these two powders.  And I'm happy to share my pet loads with any buyers after the sale.

Now... any buyer should know that EACH gun has a different chamber and velocity than others and just like the book says... you should start out a bit under the max load and ""work it up"" from there.  Also note that the books rarely have a load for a powder that didn't really fit the gun they were testing.  For example: a 30/06 is a larger bore caliber than say a .270 or an (even smaller) 25/06 has-- even thought they ALL USE the Springfield 30/06 case size for ALL these calibers.  And so THIS powder isn't a good go-to for smaller calibers (under say a .243) OR larger caliber guns with small weigh, larger diameter bullets (like the 30/06 again where this powder would shoot well, but be closer to the bottom on speed compared to other hotter powders).  BUT when you step up to a ANY Weatherby, a 25/06, 270, 280 Rem Mag, 7mm Mag, 300 Win mag-- and anything up from there (with higher velocity smaller bore bullets), this stuff works very, very well.  It would NOT be a good powder for a .308 or lighter bullets in a 30/06 or say a 30-30 because the bores are too large and the cases too small for this powder to build the pressure those calibers need.  This powder REALLY shines on the medium to heavy bullet weight range in ALL loads in larger caliber, small bore guns (as listed above and a few others too such as the 22-250, a very ""tight"" bore caliber, that might run great with this too but I haven't tested that caliber).

I can't say enough good things about this powder (obviously), but I don't go to a range every month, I don't target shoot much and the three jugs I'm keeping are basically a lifetime supply to me as a hunter.  So I thought I'd share a ""tested"" lot I confirmed to hit right at H870 and MR8700 burn rates with someone looking for a larger caliber. Mag powder they can afford and they could save their money and help me get a bit back myself too.

Read your books, look at loads for you rifle for these two common canister powers and if the book lists it, this will load the same and have the same burn rate and velocities as H870 and MR 8700 (it's basically the same size, shape, and cut ball powder as these two famous canister powders that have been around for 50 years are/were).  Remember also... the ONLY difference between a ""canister"" labeled powder Vs. a mil-surp powder is YOU have to prove it's burn rate (Vs. trusting it's label).  They ALL come from the same manufacturers folks!  And now that I HAVE proven this lot's burn rate, any buyer can safely take it (like a canister powder costing 3 times what this stuff costs) and use his/her books to work up accurate, consistent loads.  And if you are a well seasoned reloader, there are some great kicker and duplex loads I've shot MOST of this powder through and the performance has been nothing short of great.  I own a LOT of IMR, Alliant and Hogden powders on my bench and I respect them all.   This WC-857 is as consistent and accurate as any of the old favorites, it meters very nicely, and it's a SAFE powder to work with as it's a slow burner (hard to over-load) which makes it such a great fit to the larger calibers when loaded to the books.

If you don't know what you are talking about over email or at a face-to-face meeting; it is my civic and moral duty to deny you the purchase of this powder.  So please be a sincere and capable buyer or do not contact me.  Thank you."
